explanation:
Step 1: Start with (AB)(AB)⁻¹ = I and pre-multiply by A⁻¹; 
Step 2: A⁻¹(AB)(AB)⁻¹ = A⁻¹ → (A⁻¹A)B(AB)⁻¹ = A⁻¹ → I·B(AB)⁻¹ = A⁻¹; 
Step 3: Thus, B(AB)⁻¹ = A⁻¹; 
Step 4: Pre-multiply by B⁻¹ to obtain (AB)⁻¹ = B⁻¹A⁻¹. 
This completes the proof.

Step 1: Multiply A and B: 
First row, first column: 2×2 + 3×(-1) = 4 - 3 = 1; 
First row, second column: 2×(-3) + 3×2 = -6 + 6 = 0; 
Second row, first column: 1×2 + 2×(-1) = 2 - 2 = 0; 
Second row, second column: 1×(-3) + 2×2 = -3 + 4 = 1; 
Thus, AB = I. 
Step 2: Similarly verify BA = I. 
This confirms B is the inverse of A.

Step 1: Calculate determinant: det(A) = 4×6 − 7×2 = 10; 
Step 2: Write the inverse matrix as (1/det) times the matrix [[6, -7], [-2, 4]]; 
Step 3: Verify by computing A×A⁻¹ = I. 
Thus, the inverse is (1/10)*[[6, -7], [-2, 4]].

Step 1: Calculate the determinant: 3×1 - 0×5 = 3; 
Step 2: Form A⁻¹ = (1/3)*[[1, 0], [-5, 3]]; 
Step 3: Multiply A with A⁻¹ to get the identity: 
First row: 3×1/3 + 0×(-5/3) = 1, 3×0 + 0×(3/3) = 0; 
Second row: 5×1/3 + 1×(-5/3) = 0, 5×0 + 1×(3/3) = 1; 
Thus, A·A⁻¹ = I.
